                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="15765386" author="mattvryan" created="Tue, 20 Dec 2016 22:07:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Attached &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/OAK-5357&quot; title=&quot;StringUtils conversion functions can throw NullPointerException&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;OAK-5357&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;OAK-5357&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.1.patch that adds null checks.  Each function throws IllegalArgumentException if argument is null which is more in line with other argument failures.  Unit tests updated.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15765405" author="mattvryan" created="Tue, 20 Dec 2016 22:15:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m okay with just throwing NPE automatically from these functions also - but I&apos;d like to see the unit test exercise this explicitly so it is clear by looking at the code what we expected to happen in that case.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15766487" author="mduerig" created="Wed, 21 Dec 2016 08:40:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for sending a patch. I agree we need to clarify and enforce the contract wrt. nullability. I would prefer to use @Nonnull etc. annotations and &lt;tt&gt;Preconditions&lt;/tt&gt; (from Guava) to be consistent with most of the rest of Oak though. Could you update the patch to that respect? &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15796015" author="mattvryan" created="Tue, 3 Jan 2017 19:51:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Sure, I&apos;ll update the patch as requested.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15882927" author="mduerig" created="Fri, 24 Feb 2017 15:47:01 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Fixed athttp://svn.apache.org/viewvc?rev=1784288&amp;amp;view=rev&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16029039" author="edivad" created="Tue, 30 May 2017 08:38:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Bulk close for 1.7.0&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
